My dear brothers and sisters, we meet as we mourn the death of our beloved President Russell M. Nelson. I speak to you as the President of the Quorum of the Twelve, a position in which I have been sustained in our ward, stake, and general conferences for the past seven and a half years.

We will proceed with this semi-annual general conference as planned, with speakers and music assigned by President Nelson after months of preparation. The only additions are my introductory explanation and my speaking in place of President Nelson in the closing session on Sunday afternoon.

This is the first time in about 75 years that a church president has died a few days before a general conference. That required planning to hold the vital leadership meetings in connection with general conference while scheduling his funeral as soon as possible. President Nelson understood the value of general conference to provide direction to the Saints in the coming months. We honor him by following the planned conference schedule he approved.

In this time of grief we have already held a meeting to pay tribute to President Russell M. Nelson before our general conference meetings and have scheduled his funeral as soon as possible after conference. All of this has been done with the approval of President Nelson's family and the Quorum of the Twelve.

Because many assigned speakers wished to devote their time to personal tributes to President Nelson, we have asked that conference speakers keep such tributes brief, deferring elaborate tributes to the funeral, which we have begun to plan.

My brief tribute, suitable to this conference and to the tributes already paid, is this: I love Russell M. Nelson, and I have learned more about the gospel and gospel leadership from my long friendship and association with him than from any other leader I have known. He is our model as a servant and follower of the Lord Jesus Christ. Of these things I testify in the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.
